com.sri.ai.util.collect

Interface LazyIterator<T>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.util.Iterator<T>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AssignmentsIterator, CloneableFunctionIterator, FunctionIterator, LazyIteratorAdapter, NLazyIterator, PermutationIterator, SamplingAdderLazyIterator, SubKTuplesIterator, SubsetsOfKIterator

    @Beta
public interface LazyIterator<T>
extends java.util.Iterator<T>
    A lazy iterator that has the capacity to iterate over its range but only compute the actual values when required. The motivating application for this interface was a sampling iterator. While we would like the sampling iterator to be able to provide a sample at any point just like a regular iterator, it is also desirable to let it run for thousands of iteration without examining its values. In some cases, generating the actual sampled value is more expensive than simply iterating the internal variables for sampling without actually generating the value. This interface allows us to run many iterations without having to generate the value at each iteration, leading to significant performance improvement. Regular iterators do no provide this option as an interface because iteration is always accomplished by Iterator.next(), which must also return the value. Therefore, this interface adds the method goToNextWithoutComputingCurrent() for this purpose. Then computeCurrent() computes the current element when needed. Note that, while elements are not being computed, they of course cannot be used for deciding whether to keep iterator, or for deciding when to compute the element at some point. For lazy iterators, these decisions will typically be based simply on the number of iterators, or whether we have reached the end of the iterator's range. The last option can be easily achieved with computeFinalValue().

    braz
